With jest-axe 7.0.0 I'm suddenly getting the following warning:

```
Axe is already running. Use `await axe.run()` to wait for the previous run to finish before starting a new run.
```

But only for tests using `it.each`.

All other tests are fine.

The affected test is pretty simple and just renders a React component and then calls axe, of course with `await axe.run()`

```js

import { axe } from 'jest-axe';

// ...

it.each(...)('render component', async (param) {
  const { container } = render(...) // from Testing Library
  const results = await axe(container);
  expect(results).toHaveNoViolations();
});
```

This is with using the `--runInBand` CLI option, in case that makes a difference.

I believe there was recently a merge to make sure `getByTestId` only returns native elements.
https://github.com/callstack/react-native-testing-library/pull/324

Does this mean we can't use `getByTestId` on web?

In my test file in `web` says no element matches the testID, where as in `iOS` it' finds the element and my test passes.  If I switch to use a `queryByText` query, it works fine on both platforms. But I'm targeting a plain react native `<View>` to check the styling on it is expected, so I need to target by `testID`.

```js
  // Fails to find ID
  if (Platform.OS === 'web') {
    test('StickyHeader should have sticky position prop on web', () => {
      const { getByTestId } = renderRoute(<AuthenticatedApp logOut={jest.fn} user={user} />)
      const stickyHeader = getByTestId('sticky-header')
      expect(stickyHeader).toHaveStyle({ position: 'sticky' })
    })
  } 

  // Passes
  if (Platform.OS === 'ios') {
    test('StickyHeader should have relative position prop on ios ', () => {
      const { getByTestId } = renderRoute(<AuthenticatedApp logOut={jest.fn} user={user} />)
      const stickyHeader = getByTestId('sticky-header')
      expect(stickyHeader).toHaveStyle({ position: 'relative' })
    })
  }
```

debug
```js
// prints out the screen structure and I can see an object with `testID='sticky-header'`
// it also includes style object with `position: 'sticky'`, so I can see it does exist
const { debug } = renderRoute(<AuthenticatedApp logOut={jest.fn} user={user} />)
debug()
```

